\begin_layout Standard
This note outlines how to obtain relative wind and ground-referenced wind
 from the LAMS measurements.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Start in the reference frame of the LAMS, with wind components {
\begin_inset Formula $u,\, v,\, w$
\end_inset

} in that frame.
 Relative to LAMS, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the longitudinal wind (toward the tail), 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 the lateral wind (toward the port wing), and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 the vertical wind (toward the upward direction).
 The underlying coordinate system is {
\begin_inset Formula $x,\, y,\, z$
\end_inset

} with 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the forward direction, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the starboard direction, and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 downward.
 In this coordinate system, call 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta$
\end_inset

 the angle from the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi$
\end_inset

 the azimuthal rotation angle about the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-axis in the right-hand sense from the 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 axis.
 Then the sensing volumes of the three LAMS beams are approximately at {
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}\cos\Theta_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $-L_{i}\sin\Theta_{i}\sin\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}sin\Theta_{i}\cos\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

}.
 The configuration selected for testing in the September IDEAS flights is,
 approximately, {
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta,\,\Phi\}$
\end_inset

 = {{35, 180}, {35, -60}, {35, +60}} for the three beams (named here in
 the order {1,2,3}).
 The three measurements 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{1},\, a_{2},\, a_{3}\}$
\end_inset

 then are related to {
\begin_inset Formula $u,\, v,$
\end_inset

w} by the matrix of direction cosines, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

, each element of which gives the contribution of one component of {
\begin_inset Formula $u,\, v,\, w$
\end_inset

} to one component of the measurements 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{1},\, a_{2},\, a_{3}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Each direction cosine is the dot product between one of the unit vectors
 {
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{i},\,\hat{j},\,\hat{k}$
\end_inset

} representing the rectilinear 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

LAMS
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 coordinate system and one of the unit vectors {
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{1},\,\hat{b}_{2},\,\hat{b}_{3}$
\end_inset

}.
 Note that the sense of the relative wind is that positive wind is inward
 along the axis, so for example 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{i}\bullet\hat{b}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the positive quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{1}\cos\Theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and represents the contribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 to the inward velocity measured in beam #1.
 The complete set of direction cosines is then the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 giving the relationship between the rectilinear components {
\begin_inset Formula $u,\, v,\, w$
\end_inset

} and the measured inward airspeeds in the three beams {
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\, a_{2},\, a_{3}$
\end_inset

}:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}\\
a_{2}\\
a_{3}
\end{pmatrix}=\mathbf{S\,}\begin{pmatrix}u\\
v\\
w
\end{pmatrix}\label{eq:1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Evaluating these components gives
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{S}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\Theta_{1} & -\sin\Theta_{1}\sin\Phi_{1} & \sin\Theta_{1}\cos\Phi_{1}\\
\cos\Theta_{2} & -\sin\Theta_{2}\sin\Phi_{2} & \sin\Theta_{2}\cos\Phi_{2}\\
\cos\Theta_{3} & -\sin\Theta_{3}\sin\Phi_{3} & \sin\Theta_{3}\cos\Phi_{3}
\end{array}\right)\,\,\,.\label{eq:2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta_{1}=\Theta_{2}=\Theta_{3}=35^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 and {
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

}={180, -60, 60}, the matrix becomes approximately
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{S}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
0.819 & 0 & -0.574\\
0.819 & 0.497 & 0.287\\
0.819 & -0.497 & 0.287
\end{array}\right)\,\,\,.\label{eq:2-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inverting 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 then gives the wind components relative to the LAMS coordinate system in
 terms of the measured components:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{pmatrix}u\\
v\\
w
\end{pmatrix}=\mathbf{S}^{-1}\begin{pmatrix}a_{1}\\
a_{2}\\
a_{3}
\end{pmatrix}\label{eq:3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{S^{-1}}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
0.4069249 & 0.40692490 & 0.4069249\\
0 & 1.0065795 & -1.0065795\\
-1.1622979 & 0.5811489 & 0.5811489
\end{array}\right)\label{eq:4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the wind components relative to LAMS are obtained, the next step is
 to transform these to the aircraft reference frame for comparison to the
 radome-derived gust components.
 Two transformations are needed: (i) to correct for the difference in wind
 vectors at the LAMS and at the IRS that results from rotation of the aircraft
 and the offset of the LAMS sensing volumes from the location of the IRS;
 and (ii) to correct for differences in attitude angles between LAMS and
 the aircraft.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
(i) Correction for rotation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the first, Bulletin 23 gives the required correction to the relative
 wind:
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{v}_{a}^{\prime}=\vec{v}_{a}+\vec{\Omega}_{p}\times\vec{R}\label{eq:RelWindCorrection}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Omega}_{p}$
\end_inset

 is the angular rotation rate or angular velocity of the aircraft
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bulletin 23 says this is the angular acceleration but later equations make
 it clear that rotation rates like 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\phi}$
\end_inset

 are used.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{R}$
\end_inset

 is the distance from the IRS to the wind sensor.
 This footnote
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the case of LAMS, the instrument is mounted on the wing but the sensed
 wind is located at three locations ahead of the aircraft, so this transformatio
n is not as straightforward as in Bulletin 23.
 The three components {
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

} measured by LAMS need to be transformed separately, each with its own
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{R_{i}}={X_{{\rm LAMS}}+L_{i}\cos\Theta_{i},\, Y_{{\rm LAMS}}-L_{i}\sin\Theta_{i}\sin\Phi_{i},\, Z_{{\rm LAMS}}+L_{i}sin\Theta_{i}\cos\Phi_{i}}$
\end_inset

 given by the vector from the location of the IRS to the location of the
 volume sensed by the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th beam.
 In this formula, {
\begin_inset Formula $X_{{\rm LAMS}},\, Y_{{\rm LAMS}},\, Z_{{\rm LAMS}}$
\end_inset

} is the location of the LAMS relative to the IRS.
 These need to be determined accurately, but for the present purposes of
 this note I will make the guess that the coordinates of the LAMS are {-5.,
 -8., +1} m; i.e., LAMS is behind, to port, and below the IRS.
 The distances from LAMS to the focal points {
\begin_inset Formula $L_{i}$
\end_inset

} will all be taken to be 30 m, pending better information.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The rotation vector of the aircraft has components given respectively by
 the rates of change of ROLL, PITCH, and THDG (heading), expressed of course
 in radians.
 Examination of some flight data led to these approximations: {4, 0,25 2.}
 degrees per second.
 These will be used here to estimate the importance of including these correctio
ns, but for real data the derivatives of the measured attitude angles should
 be used.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and this then affects the direction cosines entering (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:2"

\end_inset

).
 Each direction cosine arises from the dot product between the unit vector
 along the beam, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

, the unit vector along each component of the relative wind: 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\alpha_{ij}=\vec{b_{i}}\bullet\vec{u_{j}}$
\end_inset

.
 However,
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The wind component sensed by the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th beam is then the dot product of the unit vector along the beam (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{b}_{i}$
\end_inset

) with the relative wind vector given by (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RelWindCorrection"

\end_inset

).
 For the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th measured component, 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
a_{i}=\sum_{j}S_{ij}(v_{j}+[\vec{\Omega}_{p}\times\vec{R}_{i}]\bullet\hat{m}_{j})\label{eq:a_i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{m}_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the appropriate unit vector from the set {
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{i},\,\hat{j},\,\hat{k}$
\end_inset

}.
 The transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v^{\prime}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 can then be written
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{S\, v}+\mathbf{C}\label{eq:9}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
C_{i}=\sum_{j}S_{ij}\,[\vec{\Omega}_{p}\times\vec{R}_{i}]\bullet\hat{m}_{j})\label{eq:Csubi}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

are then the component contributions, arising from rotation, to the airspeeds
 sensed in the three beams.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is what we discussed at our first meeting, but I now realize that it is
 unnecessarily complex.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{R}$
\end_inset

 needed in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RelWindCorrection"

\end_inset

) is only the vector from the IRS to the LAMS, without the additional extension
 to the three sample volumes, because the motion of the LAMS determines
 the rotational contribution to the measurements.
 The other components introduced by the extension from LAMS to the sample
 volumes only produce extra contributions orthogonal to the beams, and these
 then vanish when the results are multiplied to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}$
\end_inset

 to get the measured components from the rectilinear components.
 I verified this by calculation, and also verified that the calculation
 produces the same results if, instead of (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Csubi"

\end_inset

), the following equation is used:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{C}=\mathbf{S}\,\vec{\Omega}\times\vec{R}\label{eq:}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{S}\,(\mathbf{v}+\vec{\Omega}_{p}\times\vec{R})\,\,\,.\label{eq:MeasurementWithRotation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then the solution is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{S}^{-1}\mathbf{a\,-\,}\vec{\Omega}\times\vec{R}\,\,\,.\label{eq:vFromRotation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Technically, the rotation vector should be transformed into the LAMS coordinate
 frame from the aircraft frame before calculating this, but because this
 is expected to be a small correction this step will be omitted.
\end_layout

