\begin_layout Standard
The LAMS orientation is measured by a CMIGIT in the LAMS pod, while the
 aircraft orientation is measured by a fuselage-mounted IRS.
 Each measures heading, pitch, and roll.
 Transformation to the aircraft system involves transforming from the LAMS
 reference system to the aircraft reference system.
 The required transformations are described by three rotation matrices,
 defined in Bulletin 23 Eqs.
 2.5 and 2.6:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{1}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\phi & -\sin\phi\\
0 & \sin\phi & \cos\phi
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{2}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\theta & 0 & \sin\theta\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
-\sin\theta & 0 & \cos\theta
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{3}=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\cos\psi & -\sin\psi & 0\\
\sin\psi & \cos\psi & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where {
\begin_inset Formula $\phi,\,\theta,\,\psi$
\end_inset

} are {pitch, roll, heading.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because the LAMS (CMIGITS unit) is not aligned perfectly with the aircraft
 reference frame as defined by the Honeywell IRU, the relative-wind components
 measured by LAMS should first be transformed from the CMIGITS (LAMS) coordinate
 frame (attitude angles {
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{\prime},\,\theta^{\prime},\,\psi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

}) to an earth reference frame while following the proper order of transformatio
ns that corresponds to the definitions of the attitude angles.
 Then the resulting coordinates should be transformed to the Honeywell (aircraft
) coordinate system.
 Specifially, the transformation is made in the following order: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rotate by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 using the CMIGITS roll angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 to level the wings: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rotate by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 using the CMIGITS pitch angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 to level the aircraft.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rotate by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{3}$
\end_inset

 using the CMIGITS heading angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 to obtain components in a true-north reference frame.
 At this point, the relative-wind vector in an Earth-reference coordinate
 system is is 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{r}=T_{3}(T_{2}(T_{1}v))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rotate by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{3}$
\end_inset

 using the negative of the aircraft heading angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rotate by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{2}$
\end_inset

 using the negative of the aircraft pitch angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Rotate by 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1}$
\end_inset

 using the negative of the aircraft roll angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This results in relative-wind components in the reference frame of the aircraft,
 so the results can be compared to standard measurements where the relative
 wind components are {TAS, TAS*tan(SSLIP), TAS*tan(ATTACK)}.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wind components in a ground reference frame are already found at the
 end of step 3 so these should be saved for use in creating new Earth-relative
 winds.
 The procedure is relatively simple compared to routine 'gust.c' because
 all the work of rotation and transformation to Earth-reference coordinates
 has already been done, although the components are still in a coordinate
 system with {
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

} {north, east, down}.
 For example, the equations to get variables {WD_LAMS, WS_LAMS, WI_LAMS)
 analogous to {WDC, WSC, WIC} are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{g}=v_{r}+\left(\begin{array}{c}
-\mathrm{VNSC}\\
-\mathrm{VEWC}\\
\mathrm{VSPD}
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{WD_{LAMS}=\arctan2(v_{g,y},}v_{g,x})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{WS_{LAMS}=\sqrt{(v_{g,x}^{2}+v_{g,y}^{2})}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{WI_{LAMS}=v_{g,z}}
\]

\end_inset


