\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
u makes an equal contribution to all beams, as expected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the (2,1) element, with e-17, should be zero except for machine-precision
 errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
v makes equal and opposite contributions to beams 2 and 3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
w makes positive contributions to beams 2 and 3 but a negative contribution
 to beam 1.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Re Si (the inverse of S):
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The longitudinal component of the wind, 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 or TAS, is recovered by dividing the average of the three measurements
 by cos 35
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The lateral component (
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

) is almost the difference between beams 2 and 3.
 (The term with e-16 should be zero except for machine-precision errors.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
All three measurements must be used to obtain the vertical wind.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The 'Omega x R' terms give the contributions to the measured airspeeds from
 rotation, in umits of m/s.
 This rotation can produce corrections of about 0.5 m/s in the 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 component; although the correction is small it should not be neglected.
 Because the corrections are proportional to the lever arms for the rotations,
 this also indicates that knowledge of these distances to perhaps 10% is
 adequate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Differences in orientation angles between the IRS and CMIGIT reference frames
 of about 1
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 have little effect on the measured 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 component but can change 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 by more than 1.5 m/s.
 This is because a small rotation moves the large 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 component to make a significant contribution to 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 but only has a cosine-of-rotation-angle effect on 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 The relative orientation angles need to be known with low uncertainty if
 the lateral components of the wind are to be measured with low uncertainty.
 A rough estimate from this calculation is that we need to know the orientation
 angles to around 0.1
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 to determine the lateral wind components to 0.15 m/s.
\end_layout

